THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF NEVADA, REPRESENTED IN
SENATE AND ASSEMBLY, DO ENACT AS FOLLOWS:
1 Section 1. NRS 213.020 is hereby amended to read as follows:
2 213.020 1. Any person intending to apply to have a fine or forfeiture
3 remitted, a punishment commuted, a pardon granted or his or her civil rights
4 restored, or any person acting on his or her behalf, must submit an application to
5 the Board, in accordance with the procedures established by the Secretary pursuant
6 to NRS 213.017, specifying therein:
7 (a) The court in which the judgment was rendered;
8 (b) The amount of the fine or forfeiture, or the kind or character of punishment;
9 (c) The name of the person in whose favor the application is to be made;
10 (d) The particular grounds upon which the application will be based; and
11 (e) Any other information deemed relevant by the Secretary.
12 2. A person must not be required to pay a fee to have a fine or forfeiture
13 remitted, a punishment commuted, a pardon granted or his or her civil rights
14 restored pursuant to this section.
15 3. Except as otherwise provided in a policy adopted pursuant to NRS
16 213.035, the Secretary shall submit notice of the date, time and location of the
17 meeting to consider the application and one copy of the application to the district
18 attorney [and to the district judge] of the county wherein the person was convicted.
19 In cases of fines and forfeitures, notice of the date, time and location of the meeting
20 to consider the application must also be served on the chair of the board of county
21 commissioners of the county wherein the person was convicted.
22 4. Except as otherwise provided in a policy adopted pursuant to NRS
23 213.035, notice of the date, time and location of a meeting to consider an
24 application pursuant to this section must be served upon the appropriate persons as
25 required in this section at least 30 days before the presentation of the application,
26 unless a member of the Board, for good cause, prescribes a shorter time.
27 5. Nothing in this chapter shall be construed to prohibit a district judge
28 from providing factual and non-character testimony regarding the release or
29 detention of a prisoner in response to a subpoena or other formal request from
30 the Board.
31 Sec. 1.3. NRS 213.035 is hereby amended to read as follows:
32 213.035 The Board may adopt a policy to provide an expedited process to
33 take action, without holding a meeting, to restore the civil rights, in whole or in
34 part, of a person who submits an application to the Board to have his or her civil
35 rights restored if certain conditions are met, including, without limitation, that:
36 1. [There is no objection from the court in which the judgment was rendered;
37 2.] There is no objection from the district attorney of the county wherein the
38 person was convicted; and
39 [3.] 2. The Board has not received a written request for notice concerning a
40 meeting to consider an application for clemency from a victim of a crime
41 committed by the person.
42 [Section 1.] Sec. 1.7. NRS 213.10887 is hereby amended to read as
43 follows:
44 213.10887 1. The Board shall compile and maintain detailed information
45 concerning all decisions regarding parole. The information must include, but is not
46 limited to:
47 (a) The Board’s reasons for each decision to grant, deny, revoke or continue
48 parole.

